SIMPLE: sky
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sky
<hw>Sky</hw> <pr>(sk⟦imac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Skies</plw> <pr>(sk⟦imac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>skie</ets> a
cloud, Icel. <ets>sk⟦ymac⟧</ets>; akin to Sw. & Dan. <ets>sky</ets>; cf.
AS. <ets>sc⟦umac⟧a</ets>, <ets>sc⟦umac⟧wa</ets>, shadow, Icel.
<ets>skuggi</ets>; probably from the same root as E. <ets>scum</ets>.
⟦root⟧158. See <er>Scum</er>, and cf. <er>Hide</er> skin,
<er>Obscure</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A cloud.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[A wind] that blew so hideously and high,⟦br⟧
That it ne lefte not a <qex>sky</qex>⟦br⟧
In all the welkin long and broad.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a shadow.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She passeth as it were a <qex>sky</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The apparent arch, or vault, of heaven, which in a
clear day is of a blue color; the heavens; the firmament; -- sometimes
in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Norweyan banners flout the <qex>sky</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The weather; the climate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou wert better in thy grave than to answer with thy uncovered
body this extremity of the <qex>skies</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sky</xex> is often used adjectively or in the
formation of self-explaining compounds; as, <xex>sky</xex> color,
<xex>sky</xex>light, <xex>sky</xex>-aspiring, <xex>sky</xex>-born,
<xex>sky</xex>-pointing, <xex>sky</xex>-roofed, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sky blue</b></col>, <cd>an azure color.</cd> --
<col><b>Sky scraper</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a skysail of a
triangular form.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <col><b>Under open
sky</b></col>, <cd>out of doors.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Under open sky</xex>
adored.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au></cs> <-- sky scraper, a tall building,
usu. skyscraper -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sky</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sky
<hw>Sky</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Skied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Skyed</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Skying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To hang (a picture on exhibition) near the top of a wall, where it
can not be well seen.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Brother Academicians who <qex>skied</qex> his pictures.</q>
<rj><qau>The Century.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To throw towards the sky; <as>as, to <ex>sky</ex> a
ball at cricket</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sky-blue</ent>⟦br⟧
